Matthew Belloni ( https://puck.news/author/matthew-belloni/?utm_campaign=3D=
What+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F23%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27=
m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F24%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_so=
urce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Among the many ways that the internet has destroyed traditional
Hollywood: What used to constitute public relations doesn=E2=80=99t really =
work anymore. The notion of a celebrity persona crafted solely via occasion=
al media appearances seems about as quaint and outdated as a black-and-whit=
e movie or a print magazine. What matters now, in many circles, is the conv=
ersation, the constant churn of a carefully curated digital profile: media =
hits, social chatter and comments, video clips, and searchable content=E2=
=80=94both seeded and unseeded=E2=80=94that
together comprise an evolving perception of a public person.=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The old P.R. system obviously had its flaws. But it has been replaced by, e=
ssentially, guerrilla warfare=E2=80=94a 24/7 battle for attention, impressi=
ons, and sentiment, all of it subject to manipulation and, in moments of cr=
isis or vulnerability, outright implosion. The new, expanded battlefield ha=
s also empowered some of
the world=E2=80=99s worst people, trained in the dark arts of media machina=
tions and less constrained by the guardrails of traditional journalists and=
 other gatekeepers. They call themselves crisis communications experts or r=
eputation management consultants, but they are really a subset of those peo=
ple, political operatives trained to attack, obfuscate, misinform, flood th=
e zone, and, if necessary, to destroy for a price.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

At the same time, film and television stardom is much more ephemeral, both =
financially and culturally, than it used to be. The celebrity industrial co=
mplex pot of gold can now generally be found at the end of the personal bra=
nd rainbow, via the leveraging of those amorphous qualities: public persona=
, goodwill, aspiration, and, for some, talent. Commoditization has always b=
een a mostly beneficial byproduct of celebrity, but
now the cultivation of a personal brand is what matters above all else. It =
creates value amid the noise and, when managed particularly well, can turn =
average celebrities like Kylie Jenner and Selena Gomez and Ryan Reynolds in=
to billionaires.

=C2=A0

This is all a long way of explaining why the wars of perception being waged=
 online matter so much. Or why
astroturfing=E2=80=94flooding the web with content that appears to be organ=
ically produced but is actually part of a paid campaign to push an agenda, =
often to smear someone or fire back against an attempted smearing=E2=80=94i=
s now a service that certain P.R. firms casually offer on their menu, like =
a side of fries with a Double Double. And it=E2=80=99s why the battle behin=
d the scenes, and now completely engulfing, the summer hit movie It Ends Wi=
th Us has become the saddest, nastiest, and
unfortunately most cutting-edge public relations war of 2024.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

For these reasons, the publicists leading this fight=E2=80=94mostly the tea=
m allegedly smearing star Blake Lively on behalf of her co-star and produce=
r-director Justin Baldoni, but also many others involved here, both directl=
y and tangentially=E2=80=94are Hollywood=E2=80=99s Villains of the Year.=C2=
=A0=C2=A0

